        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since we are doing full Stokes, the correlator is predefined setting for continuum
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText> The main science goals require resolving the inferred magnetic field to determine the magnetic field strength and morphology.  Our HL Tau and L1527 CARMA observations have a resolution of ~50 AU, which is insufficient to constraining the full morphology since there are not enough beams across the disk, which limits morphology modeling.  In addition, most theoretical simulations show that the magnetic field morphology of the inner disk will have the most deviation from the wound-up toroidal field, eventually leading to a dominant poloidal fields launching the outflow.  Based on our previous observations, we estimate that ~20 AU is the best region to see this deviation.  

The largest scale of 1" is will allow us sensitivity to the entire disk and even the inner envelope with different weighting techniques.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our 1mm dust continuum fractional polarization result for L1527 is 2.5% on 50 AU size scale (Segura-Cox et al 2014).  As there may still be some envelope contamination, we use a conservative estimate of 1% fractional polarization, which is more consistent with our HL Tau result at 1mm (Stephen et al. 2014) and the IRAS 16293-2422 result at 850 microns (1.4%, Rao et al. 2014).  Although there is some difference in polarization with wavelength, it is a small difference at these wavelengths (e.g., Stephens et al. 2013).

The calibration of D-terms by sampling an independent polarized calibrator will provide a fractional polarization error of 0.1% and a calibrated position angle error &lt; 3 degrees, which is well-suited for our science goals.  With the 3 hours necessary for D-term calibration (ALMA handbook), the continuum 1-sigma sensitivity is 24.6 microJy.

We have direct measurements of the L1527 disk at 345 GHz with the SMA (Tobin et al. 2013), distance of a 140 pc.   we measure the disk from Tobin et al. (2013) 345 GHz dust emission and model it for ~20 AU resolution (the 0.15" resolution requested); the peak emission is 20 mJy, and the outer edge of the disk 7.5 mJy.  With a conservative 1% polarization limit, this gives a 8-sigma and 3-sigma in the peak and outer disk, respectively.

Given the fact that band 7 has a polarized grid (not an OMT), the D-terms are much more stable in band 7, giving the level of accuracy that we need for the scientific requirements of this proposal. ALMA polarization observations will be done as part of a session; thus, the initial calibrations performed as part of group 1 will be recycled in subsequent executions of the scheduling block. This scheme allows for improved efficiency giving additional time on-source than the current sensitivity calculator is estimating for the overheads.  Therefore, the 3-sigma detection in the outer disk is a conservative estimate, which we will definitely reach in a 3 hour session.

In addition, L1527 is at +26 degrees, which means it will transit at a low elevation at the ALMA site; however we do not expect this to be a problem, as L1527 has been observed by ALMA in previous cycles without polarization and lower resolution/sensitivity.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
